Introduction:¶

Natural disasters can have devastating impacts, both in terms of human lives and economic losses. Early detection of these events can be crucial in preventing their devastating consequences and one of the most promising technologies in this regard is the analysis of tweets on Twitter. There are several advantages in using Social Media to get help in this kind of situations, such as their ability to quickly provide a large amount of data, their global reach, and their ability to capture more spontaneous reactions from users, and Twitter is amongst the most popular. This makes it an invaluable tool for disaster detection, as it can provide information about the scale and severity of events much more quickly than traditional methods. By using Twitter for disaster detection, emergency responders can act more quickly and effectively in response to disasters, thus reducing their devastating impacts.

Brief Description of the Problem and Data:¶

In this Notebook, we focused on trying to be able to differentiate between a regular, random Tweet from an one that is about a Natural Disaster.

The main aim for this Notebook is to start practicing with Natural Language Processing, starting from the preprocessing phase all the way to the evaluation of the results phase.

There are 7613 entries (or rows) and five columns: id, keyword, location, text, target. The text column holds the tweet text which we will need to evaluate. We see that the text cells contain all sorts of characters such as lowercase letters, uppercase letters, numbers, punctuation, hastags (#), etc.

The Target is whether or not the text/tweet is a real disaster or not.

Data Preprocessing:¶

We will apply the following to our dataframe and text column:

  • Delete ‘location and keyword columns’
  • Remove URLs, HTMLs, https, numbers and tags
  • Delete the number of punctuations present in the dataset
  • Lowercase all words
  • Lemmatize words
  • Tokenize text

In [22]:
url_regex = 'http[s]?://(?:[a-zA-Z]|[0-9]|[$-_@.&+]|[!*\(\),]|(?:%[0-9a-fA-F][0-9a-fA-F]))+' # url

def tokenize(text):

    # get list of all urls using regex:
    
    detected_urls = re.findall(url_regex, text)
    
    # replace each url in text string with placeholder:
    
    text = text.lower() # To lowercase
    text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text) # Remove digits
    text = re.sub(r'@([a-z0-9]+)|#',  '', text) # Remove tags
    text = re.sub('\[.*?\]', '', text) # Remove html
    text = re.sub('[%s]' % re.escape(string.punctuation), '', text) # Remove punctuations
    
    for url in detected_urls:
        text = text.replace(url_regex, 'urlplaceholder') # Remove https

    words = word_tokenize(text)
    
    tokens = ' '.join([ele for ele in words if ele not in stopwords.words('english')])
    
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer() # Lemmatizing
    
    texts = ' '.join(lemmatizer.lemmatize(tok) for tok in tokens.split(' '))

    return texts # Cleaned text

Model Architecure:¶

The training data is all ready to go for the models. We will first split the data into training and testing sets.

For this project we decided to do two RNN models: LSTM and GRU.

Both models are very simple to show how training a RNN model does not have to be complex. In fact LSTM and GRU models are similar in build as when building other neural networks, especially using Tensorflow Keras frameworks.

Our LSTM model will have a Dropout and LSTM layer in its network. The GRU model will have an Bidirectional GRU layer. Both models will have an Embedding layer and Dense layer. For consistency, the output layers will have a sigmoid activation function, with an Adam loss function and a learning rate of 0.0001. During training, we will measure accuracy, loss, precision, and recall.

LSTM, Long-Short Term Memory models are a type of Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) which has specific gates to process the data. You can find more here and/or here which are great introductory resources into the mechancis of LSTM.

GRU, Gated Recurrent Unit is another great RNN model to test with text data. Generally, GRUs perform better than LSTM models and can be faster.

LSTM MODEL:¶

In [27]:
# First lstm model:

lstm_model = Sequential()

lstm_model.add(Embedding(input_dim = 20000,  output_dim = 32, input_length = X_train.shape[1]))
lstm_model.add(LSTM(units = 60, activation = 'relu'))
lstm_model.add(Dropout(0.1))
lstm_model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))
               
optimizers = Adam(learning_rate = 0.001) # Optimizer
               
lstm_model.compile(loss = 'binary_crossentropy', optimizer = optimizers, metrics = ['accuracy']) # Compiling

lstm_model.summary() # Summary

gru_model = Sequential()

gru_model.add(Bidirectional(GRU(units = 40)))
gru_model.add(Dropout(0.1))

The first model using LSTM techniques got an F1 score of 0.556, which is better than the GRU model which got an F1 score of 0.541 on the test set. These values are a bit better than randomly guessing.

Conclusion:¶

Firstly we have imported the training dataset and analyzed it. We also visualized much of the data too. Then we preprocessed the training data and modified the text by making it easier for a computer to understand. After we had the training data ready, we split the training data into two subsets; training and validation, so that we could better train our models. Then we trained two models; LSTM and GRU. Finally, we tested both models on the testing set and found our F1 score in the Kaggle competition page.

Overall, both the models performed less than we had hoped. However, these two models were both very simple and probably were overfitting to the training data. Based on the graphs showing the different metrics per epoch used in each model, we thought we had a good idea of how the models would perform; they seemed to be doing well. We could have gotten better results with more data, different text cleaning methods, fewer epochs to prevent overfitting.
